ADMIN View:
All Leave Requests Table:
Employee	Leave Type	Start - End	Days	Status	Actions
John Doe	Annual	12/20 - 12/22	3	ðŸŸ¡ Pending	Approve / Deny
Jane Smith	Medical	12/10 - 12/11	2	ðŸŸ¡ Pending	Approve / Deny
MANAGER View:
Department Leave Requests (same as ADMIN, but filtered to managed department)
Leave Types:
1.	Annual Leave - Vacation, planned time off
2.	Medical Leave - Sick leave, medical appointments
3.	Personal Leave - Personal matters, emergencies
Status Indicators:
â€¢	ðŸŸ¡ PENDING: Awaiting manager approval
â€¢	âœ… APPROVED: Manager approved request
â€¢	âŒ REJECTED: Manager denied request
Features for EMPLOYEE:
â€¢	âœ… Submit new leave requests
â€¢	âœ… Edit PENDING requests
â€¢	âœ… Delete PENDING requests
â€¢	âœ… View all personal requests with status
â€¢	âŒ Cannot approve/deny any requests
Features for ADMIN/MANAGER:
â€¢	âœ… View leave requests (all or department)
â€¢	âœ… Approve requests with one click
â€¢	âœ… Deny requests with one click
â€¢	âœ… Filter by status (Pending/Approved/Rejected)
â€¢	âœ… View employee details
Form Validation:
â€¢	Leave type required
â€¢	Start date required
â€¢	End date required
â€¢	End date must be >= start date
â€¢	Reason required (min 10 characters)
Business Rules:
1.	Cannot submit leave for past dates
2.	Cannot edit/delete approved or rejected requests
3.	System calculates total leave days automatically
4.	Managers can only approve for their department
5.	Admins can approve any request
API Endpoints:
â€¢	GET /api/leaves - List leaves (filtered by role)
â€¢	GET /api/leaves/{id} - Get leave details
â€¢	POST /api/leaves - Submit leave request
â€¢	PUT /api/leaves/{id} - Update pending request
â€¢	DELETE /api/leaves/{id} - Delete pending request
â€¢	POST /api/leaves/{id}/approve - Approve request
â€¢	POST /api/leaves/{id}/reject - Reject request
â€¢	GET /api/leaves/pending - Get pending requests only
6. DEVELOPMENT NOTES
6.1 Security Considerations
Current Implementation (Development):
â€¢	âš ï¸ Passwords stored as plain text
â€¢	âš ï¸ JWT secret hardcoded in source
â€¢	âš ï¸ No HTTPS enforcement
â€¢	âš ï¸ LocalStorage used for token storage (vulnerable to XSS)
Production Recommendations:
*	Password Security: 
o	âœ… Use BCrypt hashing (already imported, not used)
o	âœ… Implement password strength requirements
o	âœ… Add password reset functionality
*	Token Security: 
o	âœ… Use HttpOnly cookies instead of localStorage
o	âœ… Implement refresh tokens
o	âœ… Shorten token expiration (15-30 minutes)
o	âœ… Use secure, randomly generated JWT secret
o	âœ… Store secrets in environment variables
* HTTPS: 
o	âœ… Enable SSL/TLS in production
o	âœ… Use HSTS headers
o	âœ… Redirect HTTP to HTTPS
*	Input Validation: 
o	âœ… Validate all inputs on backend
o	âœ… Use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
o	âœ… Sanitize user inputs
*	Rate Limiting: 
o	âœ… Implement rate limiting on login endpoint
o	âœ… Add CAPTCHA for failed login attempts
6.2 Known Limitations
*	No Email Functionality: 
o	No email verification on registration
o	No password reset emails
o	No leave approval notifications
*	Limited File Upload: 
o	Cannot upload profile pictures
o	Cannot attach documents to leave requests
*	No Real-Time Updates: 
o	Page must be refreshed to see changes
o	No WebSocket for live attendance updates
*	Basic Reporting: 
o	Limited report generation
o	No export to PDF/Excel functionality
* Mobile Responsiveness: 
o	Layout optimized for desktop
o	Mobile UI needs improvement
* No Audit Trail: 
o	Limited logging of user actions
o	No change history for records
6.3 Future Enhancements
Priority 1 (Security):
â€¢	Implement BCrypt password hashing
â€¢	Use HttpOnly cookies for tokens
â€¢	Add refresh token mechanism
â€¢	Implement account lockout after failed logins
Priority 2 (Features):
â€¢	Email notifications for leave approvals
â€¢	Export reports to PDF/Excel
â€¢	Mobile-responsive design
â€¢	Profile picture upload
â€¢	Advanced reporting dashboard
Priority 3 (UX Improvements):
â€¢	Real-time notifications
â€¢	Drag-and-drop shift scheduling
â€¢	Calendar view for attendance
â€¢	Employee self-service portal
â€¢	Manager dashboard with team overview
Priority 4 (Scalability):
â€¢	Database connection pooling
â€¢	Redis caching layer
â€¢	Load balancing support
â€¢	Microservices architecture
â€¢	Docker containerization
6.4 Testing Strategy
Manual Testing Checklist:
â€¢	Login with ADMIN role
â€¢	Login with MANAGER role
â€¢	Login with EMPLOYEE role
â€¢	Create new employee
â€¢	Update employee details
â€¢	Delete employee
â€¢	Create department
â€¢	Assign manager to department
â€¢	Create shift
â€¢	Employee check-in
â€¢	Employee check-out
â€¢	Admin mark attendance
â€¢	Submit leave request
â€¢	Approve leave request
â€¢	Reject leave request
â€¢	Add holiday
â€¢	View attendance by date
â€¢	Logout and verify token invalidation
Automated Testing (Future):
â€¢	Unit tests for services
â€¢	Integration tests for controllers
â€¢	End-to-end tests with Selenium
â€¢	Load testing with JMeter
6.5 Code Style Guidelines
Backend (Java):
â€¢	Use camelCase for variables and methods
â€¢	Use PascalCase for class names
â€¢	Always use @Override annotation
â€¢	Add JavaDoc comments for public methods
â€¢	Keep methods under 30 lines
Frontend (JavaScript):
â€¢	Use const/let, never var
â€¢	Use arrow functions
â€¢	Use async/await for promises
â€¢	Add JSDoc comments for functions
â€¢	Use meaningful variable names
Database:
â€¢	Use PascalCase for table names
â€¢	Use camelCase for column names
â€¢	Always define foreign key constraints
â€¢	Add indexes for frequently queried columns
â€¢	Use ENUM for fixed value sets
6.6 Deployment Guide
Development Deployment:
1.	Start MySQL on port 3306
2.	Run backend: mvn spring-boot:run
3.	Run frontend:  server.js
4.	Access: http://localhost:8081/UserLogin.html
Production Deployment (Example with AWS):
1.	Database: Amazon RDS for MySQL
2.	Backend: AWS Elastic Beanstalk or EC2
3.	Frontend: S3 + CloudFront CDN
4.	Load Balancer: Application Load Balancer
5.	SSL Certificate: AWS Certificate Manager
Docker Deployment:
dockerfile
 Backend Dockerfile
FROM openjdk:17-jdk-slim
COPY target/*.jar app.jar
EXPOSE 8080
ENTRYPOINT ["java","-jar","/app.jar"]

 Frontend Dockerfile
FROM :16-alpine
WORKDIR /app
COPY . .
EXPOSE 8081
CMD ["", "server.js"]

 docker-compose.yml
version: '3.8'
services:
  mysql:
    image: mysql:8.0
    environment:
      MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD: root
      MYSQL_DATABASE: employee_attendance
    ports:
      - "3306:3306"
  
  backend:
    build: ./backend
    ports:
      - "8080:8080"
    depends_on:
      - mysql
  
  frontend:
    build: ./frontend
    ports:
      - "8081:8081"
    depends_on:
      - backend
6.7 Database Backup & Recovery
Backup Command (MySQL):
bash
mysqldump -u root -p employee_attendance > backup_$(date +%Y%m%d).sql
Restore Command:
bash
mysql -u root -p employee_attendance < backup_20241207.sql
Automated Backup Script:
bash
!/bin/bash
DATE=$(date +%Y%m%d_%H%M%S)
BACKUP_DIR="/backups"
DB_NAME="employee_attendance"

mysqldump -u root -p${DB_PASS} ${DB_NAME} > ${BACKUP_DIR}/backup_${DATE}.sql

 Keep only last 7 days of backups
find ${BACKUP_DIR} -name "backup_*.sql" -mtime +7 -delete
6.8 Monitoring & Logging
Backend Logging (application.properties):
properties
* Enable SQL logging
spring.jpa.show-sql=true
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.format_sql=true

* Logging levels
logging.level.root=INFO
logging.level.employeeAttendanceSystem=DEBUG
logging.level.org.springframework.security=DEBUG

* Log file
logging.file.name=logs/application.log
logging.file.max-size=10MB
logging.file.max-history=30
Recommended Monitoring Tools:
â€¢	Application Performance: Spring Boot Actuator
â€¢	Database Performance: MySQL Slow Query Log
â€¢	Error Tracking: Sentry or Rollbar
â€¢	Uptime Monitoring: UptimeRobot or Pingdom
7. APPENDIX
7.1 Database Schema Reference
UserLogin Table:
sql
CREATE TABLE UserLogin (
    UserID INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    Username VARCHAR(50) UNIQUE NOT NULL,
    PasswordHash VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,
    Role ENUM('ADMIN', 'MANAGER', 'EMPLOYEE') NOT NULL,
    Last_login TIMESTAMP NULL,
    created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
);
Employee Table:
sql
CREATE TABLE Employee (
    EmployeeID INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    Name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    Ssn VARCHAR(20) UNIQUE,
    Address VARCHAR(255),
    Email VARCHAR(100) UNIQUE NOT NULL,
    Salary DECIMAL(10, 2),
    Sex ENUM('MALE', 'FEMALE'),
    Birthday DATE,
    UserID INT UNIQUE,
    DepartmentID INT,
    Created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    FOREIGN KEY (UserID) REFERENCES UserLogin(UserID),
    FOREIGN KEY (DepartmentID) REFERENCES Department(DepartmentID)
);
Department Table:
sql
CREATE TABLE Department (
    DepartmentID INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    Department_name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    Location VARCHAR(255),
    ManagerEmployeeID INT,
    created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    updated_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP ON UPDATE CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    FOREIGN KEY (ManagerEmployeeID) REFERENCES Employee(EmployeeID)
);
Shift Table:
sql
CREATE TABLE Shift (
    ShiftID INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    Shift_name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
    Start_time TIME NOT NULL,
    End_time TIME NOT NULL
);
Attendance Table:
sql
CREATE TABLE Attendance (
    AttendanceID INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    EmployeeID INT NOT NULL,
    WorkDate DATE NOT NULL,
    ShiftID INT,
    CheckIn TIMESTAMP,
    CheckOut TIMESTAMP,
    Status ENUM('PRESENT', 'ABSENT', 'LEAVE', 'HOLIDAY', 'LATE'),
    created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    HolidayID INT,
    FOREIGN KEY (EmployeeID) REFERENCES Employee(EmployeeID),
    FOREIGN KEY (ShiftID) REFERENCES Shift(ShiftID),
    FOREIGN KEY (HolidayID) REFERENCES Holiday(HolidayID),
    UNIQUE KEY unique_attendance (EmployeeID, WorkDate)
);
Holiday Table:
sql
CREATE TABLE Holiday (
    HolidayID INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    HolidayName VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    HolidayDate DATE NOT NULL UNIQUE,
    Description TEXT
);
LeaveType Table:
sql
CREATE TABLE LeaveType (
    LeaveTypeID INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    LeaveType_name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
    MaxDaysAllowed INT NOT NULL
);
LeaveRecord Table:
sql
CREATE TABLE LeaveRecord (
    LeaveID INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    EmployeeID INT NOT NULL,
    LeaveTypeID INT NOT NULL,
    Start_date DATE NOT NULL,
    End_date DATE NOT NULL,
    Reason TEXT,
    Status ENUM('PENDING', 'APPROVED', 'REJECTED') DEFAULT 'PENDING',
    created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    FOREIGN KEY (EmployeeID) REFERENCES Employee(EmployeeID),
    FOREIGN KEY (LeaveTypeID) REFERENCES LeaveType(LeaveTypeID)
);
7.2 Environment Variables (Production)
bash
- Database
DB_HOST=localhost
DB_PORT=3306
DB_NAME=employee_attendance
DB_USER=app_user
DB_PASSWORD=secure_password_here

- JWT
JWT_SECRET=your_super_secure_random_secret_key_here
JWT_EXPIRATION=86400000

- Server
SERVER_PORT=8080
FRONTEND_URL=http://localhost:8081

- Email (Future)
SMTP_HOST=smtp.gmail.com
SMTP_PORT=587
SMTP_USER=noreply@company.com
SMTP_PASSWORD=email_password_here

- AWS (Future)
AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=your_access_key
AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=your_secret_key
AWS_REGION=us-east-1
S3_BUCKET=employee-attendance-uploads
7.3 Useful SQL Queries
Get all employees with department names:
sql
SELECT e.EmployeeID, e.Name, e.Email, d.Department_name
FROM Employee e
LEFT JOIN Department d ON e.DepartmentID = d.DepartmentID;
Get today's attendance summary:
sql
SELECT 
    COUNT(*) as total_employees,
    SUM(CASE WHEN a.CheckIn IS NOT NULL THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as checked_in,
    SUM(CASE WHEN a.Status = 'ABSENT' THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as absent
FROM Employee e
LEFT JOIN Attendance a ON e.EmployeeID = a.EmployeeID AND a.WorkDate = CURDATE();
Get employees with pending leave requests:
sql
SELECT e.Name, lr.Start_date, lr.End_date, lr.Reason
FROM LeaveRecord lr
JOIN Employee e ON lr.EmployeeID = e.EmployeeID
WHERE lr.Status = 'PENDING'
ORDER BY lr.created_at DESC;
Get attendance rate by department:
sql
SELECT 
    d.Department_name,
    COUNT(DISTINCT e.EmployeeID) as total_employees,
    COUNT(DISTINCT CASE WHEN a.Status = 'PRESENT' THEN a.EmployeeID END) as present_count,
    ROUND(COUNT(DISTINCT CASE WHEN a.Status = 'PRESENT' THEN a.EmployeeID END) * 100.0 / COUNT(DISTINCT e.EmployeeID), 2) as attendance_rate
FROM Department d
JOIN Employee e ON d.DepartmentID = e.DepartmentID
LEFT JOIN Attendance a ON e.EmployeeID = a.EmployeeID AND a.WorkDate = CURDATE()
GROUP BY d.DepartmentID, d.Department_name;
7.4 Git Workflow

**Branching Strategy:**
```
main (production-ready)
  â”œâ”€â”€ develop (latest development)
  â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ feature/employee-management
  â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ feature/attendance-tracking
  â”‚   â””â”€â”€ feature/leave-system
  â””â”€â”€ hotfix/critical-bug-fix
```

**Commit Message Format:**
```
<type>(<scope>): <subject>

[optional body]
[optional footer]

Types: feat, fix, docs, style, refactor, test, chore
Example: feat(attendance): add check-in validation
Useful Git Commands:
bash
 Create feature branch
git checkout -b feature/new-feature

 Commit changes
git add .
git commit -m "feat(module): add new feature"

 Push to remote
git push origin feature/new-feature

 Merge to develop
git checkout develop
git merge feature/new-feature

 Tag release
git tag -a v1.0.0 -m "Release version 1.0.0"
git push origin v1.0.0



